Not as good as Happy Hour, or Wheel of Fortune and Fantasy, but still pretty good.

>most pathetic conclusion ever
Maybe not great, but it wasn't too bad. As someone who liked the film, it felt a little anticlimactic.

>A literal cuckold who never confronts his wife or the man who slept with her, and basically embraces it after somehow being convinced his wife was a great person and not just an unfaithful bitch.
It's been a while since I've seen it, but I don't think that he ever "embraces being a cuckold". It's more that his repressed resentment over it all and the lack of closure dissipates when he gets that kind of "let he who is without sin cast the first stone" revelation after reflecting on his own agency in the relationship after having her side presented to him in that car ride with the the young guy. As I see it, it's not about exonerating her entirely (she was not entitled to cheat because she didn't feel tingles and the indirectness of her own communication obviously left a lot to be desired), but it is about the valuable point that being "hard" (at least more rigorous in introspection, self-scrutiny, analysis of situations, and resolve in self-control and taking initiative) on yourself (the person over whom you have the most control) and gentler on others (especially those whom you love for the obvious reason that you love them) is essentially the right way. I'm the same. I remember enjoying the first film in cinemas but purely only for the effects/technology and the fact I was an easily impressed teenager. Rewatching it afterwards left me very turned off from further movies. But I watched TWOW just cause nothing else was on and I really did not expect to be THAT impressed by the CGI and overall production quality. I think this film is even further ahead in terms of spectacle and special effects compared to other 2022 films, than the first film was compared to other films from 2009. And after over a decade of near constant soulless regurgitated slop by Marvel that feels like it gets uglier and less creative as years go by, Avatar 2 is just a genuinely well made classic blockbuster with as much attention as possible paid to making a spectacle that wows with every shot. While the story is very basic, I even found myself enjoying the characters and liking things like the fact there is a respectable and caring father figure portrayed on film, or a simple yet effective coming of age story for a group of likable new young characters. I think I will watch it again so I can see if 3D makes a difference, but really even in 2D I am happy to have a film that is genuinely worth going to the cinema for, the only one this year after Top Gun Maverick.

To his credit Eggers strived for historical authenticity with a few noticeable but not overly distracting exceptions (the slaves playing a ball game comes to mind) and as an autist who has a pretty good stack of books about vikings I kept being impressed by Eggers' attention to detail.
